-- Gold Set for First Weekly Decline in Six as Dollar's Strength Cuts Appeal
-- B y   W e n d y   P u g h
-- 2010-10-22T01:57:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-22/gold-set-for-first-weekly-decline-in-six-as-dollar-s-strength-cuts-appeal.html
Gold headed for its first weekly
decline in six as a rebound in the dollar eroded the metal’s
appeal as a haven against debasement of the U.S. currency.  Bullion for immediate delivery traded little changed at
$1,326.65 an ounce at 12:39 p.m. Melbourne time, down 4.4
percent from the Oct. 14 record of $1,387.35, and taking the
weekly drop to 3.1 percent. The dollar gained against a basket
of six currencies, poised to end a five-week slump.  “The market is unsure that we will reach new highs,” said
 Jonathan Barratt , managing director of Commodity Broking
Services Pty in Sydney. “You are seeing a realignment of
people’s ideals to the value of gold given that the U.S. dollar
perhaps has reached an intermediate low for some time.”  Gold rallied for the past five weeks on speculation that
the Federal Reserve may further ease monetary policy, hurting
the dollar. The currency gained today amid speculation Group of
20 finance ministers meeting in South Korea today and tomorrow
will agree to refrain from weakening their currencies in a bid
to soothe trade tensions before they derail the global economy.  Gold for December delivery in New York gained 0.1 percent
to $1,327 an ounce after slumping 1.4 percent yesterday, taking
this week’s drop to 3.3 percent. The most-active futures
contract touched an all-time high Oct. 14 of $1,388.10.  The dollar was at $1.3900 per euro at 9:29 a.m. in Tokyo
from $1.3920 in New York yesterday. The greenback rose 0.1
percent against a basket of six currencies, taking this week’s
advance to 0.6 percent.  Finance Ministers  Global finance ministers are planning to say members will
refrain from “competitive undervaluation” of currencies,
according to an official from a G-20 country, citing a draft
statement and speaking on condition of anonymity.  U.S. Treasury Secretary  Timothy Geithner  told Brazil’s
Finance Minister Guido Mantega on Oct. 21 that the U.S. won’t
allow the dollar to weaken, Mantega said yesterday.  Ten of 19 traders, investors and analysts surveyed by
Bloomberg, or 53 percent, said that gold will fall next week as
some investors sell the metal after its rally to a record.
Seven forecast higher prices and two were neutral.  Silver rose 0.4 percent to $23.2744 an ounce after dropping
3.2 percent yesterday. Platinum was little changed at $1,673.38
an ounce, while palladium gained 0.3 percent to $589.38 an ounce
after reaching a nine-year high of $605.13 last week.  To contact the reporter on this story:
